# Ubiquitous Language Glossary

This document defines the shared language used by both the business stakeholders and the development team[cite: 1]. Adhering to this glossary ensures consistency across the requirements, the domain model, and the implementation code[cite: 1].

## 1. Domain Business Terms
These terms represent the core concepts and real-world entities of the **Event Ticketing & Booking System**[cite: 1].

| Term | Meaning |
| :--- | :--- |
| **Event** | An activity organized by an Event Organizer and attended by customers[cite: 1]. |
| **Event Organizer** | A user who creates and manages events, ticket categories, and refunds[cite: 1]. |
| **Customer** | A user who browses events, creates bookings, and purchases tickets[cite: 1]. |
| **Gate Officer** | A user who validates unique ticket codes during event check-in[cite: 1]. |
| **System Admin** | A user responsible for triggering refund payouts and monitoring operations[cite: 1]. |
| **Ticket Category** | A specific type of ticket (e.g., Regular, VIP) with its own price and quota[cite: 1]. |
| **Quota** | The maximum number of tickets available within a specific ticket category[cite: 1]. |
| **Booking** | A temporary reservation of tickets before payment is finalized[cite: 1]. |
| **Ticket** | Official proof of attendance generated only after a booking is successfully paid[cite: 1]. |
| **Ticket Code** | A unique identifier used to validate a ticket at the venue[cite: 1]. |
| **Check-in** | The process of validating a ticket when a participant enters the event[cite: 1]. |
| **Refund** | The process of returning money to a customer for a cancelled or requested booking[cite: 1]. |
| **Money** | A value object representing a specific amount and its currency[cite: 1]. |
| **Sales Period** | The timeframe during which a specific ticket category is available for purchase[cite: 1]. |
| **Payment Deadline** | The time limit (e.g., 15 minutes) to pay for a booking before it expires[cite: 1]. |

## 2. Technical & Architectural Terms (DDD)
These terms represent the architectural patterns and components required for the **Clean Architecture** and **Domain-Driven Design** implementation[cite: 1].

| Term | Meaning in Implementation |
| :--- | :--- |
| **Aggregate** | A cluster of domain objects treated as a single unit for data changes[cite: 1]. |
| **Entity** | A domain object with a unique identity that persists over time[cite: 1]. |
| **Value Object** | An object defined only by its attributes with no unique identity (e.g., `Money`)[cite: 1]. |
| **Domain Event** | A notification of a significant change within the domain logic[cite: 1]. |
| **Repository** | An interface for persisting and retrieving Aggregates from the database[cite: 1]. |
| **Domain Service** | Business logic that doesn't naturally belong inside a single Entity or Aggregate[cite: 1]. |
| **Command** | An object representing an intent to change the state of the system[cite: 1]. |
| **Query** | An object representing a request to retrieve data without changing it[cite: 1]. |
| **Handler** | The specific logic that executes a Command or a Query[cite: 1]. |
| **DTO** | Data Transfer Object used to move data between layers[cite: 1]. |

